{"id":"1402.3311","submitter":"L\\'eo Gerville-R\\'eache","authors":"L\\'eo Gerville-R\\'eache","title":"Why do we change whatever amount we found in the first envelope: the\n  Wikipedia \"two envelopes problem\" commented","comments":"Preprint - 17 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.HO math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyze the main arguments that attempt to explain why there is no point\nin changing the envelope. Most people confuse estimation and calculation,\nconditional and unconditional probabilities, random and non-random variables,\nmodelling and reality, chance and uncertainty (or credence), whatever X known\nand whatever X unknown, personal and interpersonal estimates. Such confusions\nsuggest that there would be no point in swapping the envelope. Our analysis is\nthat if the first envelope is opened, whatever the amount, it is rational and\nconsistent to think that it is worth changing it. If the first envelope is not\nopened, it is rational and consistent to believe there is no point in swapping\nthe envelope.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Feb 2014 15:57:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-02-17"}
